C:\OSCAD> cd OSCAD

C:\OSCAD\OSCAD> cd forntEnd

C:\OSCAD\OSCAD\forntEnd>python oscad.py
'python' is not recognized as an internal or external command,
operable program or batch file.


Apparently, I found a way to 'fix' this. I opened cmd, and typed out all of the above manually. the last command I changed to "oscad.py" instead of "python oscad.py", and the little window with the OSCAD logo opened. But when I created a new project, only the Toolkit appeared, and no workspace was on the screen.

???

title: Can show bigger handles

title: Gradient tool mouse click not shown
body: When you introduced gradient tool first time, you should have allowed the viewer "see" where it is.  Although the tool name appears on the screen, it does so only momentarily - possibly, we can show it for about 2 to 3 seconds to let people "see" it without rewinding.  Rule 2.1.2 of the checklist, in fact, explains it.

title: Stroke paint tab mentioned wrongly
body:
The narrator says "click on the stroke paint tab and then the rectangle".  She meant "click on the selection tool and then the rectangle".  This is a minor mistake and hence possibly can be left alone, as by now, the learner may know what is meant. 

This should be corrected at least in the dubbing.

title: Use direct sentence, not indirect
body:
"You can increase or decrease the outline using the Stroke Style tab" is indirect and makes it difficult to understand, as this activity is being introduced first time.  The adopted sequence shows the action first and then tell how to do it.  The viewer has to rewind once or twice more to understand what is being done.  As the reader has to do the above activity in reverse direction, I call this "reverse direction" style or "indirect direction" style.  This style should be avoided when a new topic is introduced to make it friendly to the beginners.

Instead, the narrator should say something like the following: "We will next show how to increase the thickness of the outline.  Press the stroke style tab.  Using the arrow keys, one can increase or decrease the tab." I call this the "direct narration" style.  The direct narration style should be used, if we want to be novice friendly.

title: One has to necessarily zoom to see this effect
body: One has to necessarily zoom to see the effect of the stroke style action.  I tried this action without zooming and I thought that this feature was not working in my installation.  After some experimentation, I realised that the drawings on the tab are somewhat exaggerated and that the actual effect of this action may not be visible without zooming.

title: Open source for school Students
body:
In all schools mostly from class 2 onwards, Windows and MS office is taught to students, making them aware and user friendly to Microsoft products from childhood, as part of curriculum. Today majority of graduates or collegians are reluctant to learn Linux or other open source, as they are used to MS Win / MS Office everywhere. Majority of our staff is reluctant to use Open source software, due to several practical issues.

Even Govt. aided course MS CIT run by thousands of classes across Maharashtra under MKCL teaches MS products, and its certificate is must in most Govt. organizations for employment.

Hardly any school or such classes promote or teach FOSS.

Why can't FOSS - Linux and Libre/Open office at least, taught in schools, to teachers and students as well as introduced as part of curriculum or on MKCL run courses, so that in coming years, students are already literate on FOSS.

This is not a question, but more of a suggestion from my side. Thanks.

title: Please Support India's Own BOSSLINUX by signing the petiotion
body:
Hi All !

I've started the petition "India's Honorable Prime Minister Shree Narendra Modi: Implement India's Own Operating System 'Bharat Operating System (BOSS)' immediately in State and Central Government Offices, Schools, Colleges and Universities in place of Microsoft Windows by an Ordinance" and need your help to get it off the ground.

Will you take 30 seconds to sign it right now? Here's the link:

http://www.change.org/p/india-s-honorable-prime-minister-shree-narendra-modi-implement-india-s-own-operating-system-bharat-operating-system-boss-immediately-in-state-and-central-government-offices-schools-colleges-and-universities-in-place-of-microsoft-windows-by-an-ordina

Here's why it's important:

Corruption in our country (India) has increased to such a great extent that you do not require ACB, CBI, SIT or any sting operation. Thanks to technology era. Just with a few clicks you get all evidences of corruption and also thanks to RTI which is now available online !

Please watch the beautiful video  https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uO7slEkFP-g  from you tube  (Duration 1 Min 3 sec)

It is created by our own Government of India for promotion of India's software achievement -- BOSS , to replace Microsoft Windows. Note the upload date - 1 June 2010. Obviously the video is made for promotion and free distribution of BOSS DVD's to school, college students, in villages and to common man. It was made for National Channel and was to be shown regularly as it is done for similar schemes (Beti Bachao, Swachhata Abhiyan, Polio, Shauchalaya etc). But this video is perhaps blocked by Censor Board or Government (for about 5 years !). The reasons are best known to themselves.
I have really failed to realize any thing objectionable in the video or in the Lyrics which goes like this

Dil Ki Soch Daud Rahi Hai
Kal Ki Shan Ko Hasil Karne
Aaj Yanha !

Unglia Nache Subkuch Sikhe
Pragati Prerana Pal Pal Paye
Aaj Yahna !

Apna Khayal, Apne Sapne
Pagaye, Pankh Naye
Hum Udenge, Aap Udenge
Aaa Gaya, Aaa Gaya
Naya BOSS !

Ye Bharat Ki Shan Hai !          ( It is pride of India )
Duniya Me Pehachan Hai !     (It is the Identity of India in the World)

BHARAT OPERATING SYSTEM SOLUTIONS (BOSS)

In fact when I show this video to a common person, his/her face shines with joy and pride for the country. Then I ask - do you really know that our country has made its own operating system for the sole purpose replacing Microsoft Windows ? He/she says No ! Then I ask , why this video has not been shown on National channel for last five years if the DVD was to be distributed freely across the country ?

The unique answer comes out quite naturally , after a pause, Corruption ! To create fertile ground for Microsoft !

The common man is right. BOSS is free, open source and perfect replacement for Microsoft Windows, it could have saved trillions of dollars (or more..) for our country in last five years.
India could have also avoided the slavery and dependency that we are facing today. ( Unfortunately most of the Indians are not aware of this slavery and on the contrary believe that India will be a Superpower).

Then question comes.... what are the benefits and drawbacks of this Bharat Operating System ? There are plenty of benefits and no drawbacks. I show them official government document of benefits -- Tamilnadu GO dated 12 March 2014, (You can get it on internet). Common man is not aware that Tamilnadu Government has made it mandatory. Then question comes why not in our own state ? I have no answer ...

AFAIK no school, college , university has received the free DVD's through UGC,Education Departments and through publicly announced programs and circulars, despite the fact that special version of BOSS, "EduBoss" is created for Education Field !

The BOSS DVD is completely free. As per the free scheme on BOSS site (www.bosslinux.in) I registered with my email, address and mob number and after a few days, I received a free BOSS DVD. Then many of my friends tried to register and procure BOSS DVD but to their surprise, site was down for technical problems ! ( Coincidence ?!). No one has received DVD after it is delivered to me. Site is still closed as of today 11/4/2015 for more than one month.

Every news regarding BOSS is always on 3rd, 4th,5th page and that is also in news papers such as Economic Times, Financial Express etc but the DVD is supposed to be distributed to common man, even in villages ! Every activity and project related to BOSS is kept as a secret although it is "Bharat Ki Shan Hai, Duniya Me Pehechan Hai !"

I had filed an RTI (Reg No. DITEC/R/2015/60052) to Information and Technology Ministry (The Ministry who created BOSS to replace MS Windows !). I asked them how much amount was spent to purchase MS Windows only in one financial year 2013-14. I was shocked to see the reply - Rs 1,18,77,136/- Taxes Extra ! They have already spent thousands of crores on CDAC to create BOSS as replacement for MS Windows, how can they spend such huge public fund to again buy MS Windows when BOSS was ready to replace MS Windows right from June 2010 ? This is the case of only one office and one financial year. You can imagine the expenditure in all central and state government Offices, Schools, Colleges and Universities. India can never become a Superpower if such huge foreign currency is spent on non-tangible software products which are easily available and made available by the government absolutely and legally free. You realize now why so much secrecy is maintained about BOSS which is a pride of our country !

Another interesting thing is that "Make In India" is one of the most Ambitious Project of our Honorable Prime Minister Shree Narendra Modiji but most of the people do not know that BOSS is a part of "Make In India". (See financial express dated 12 Jan 2015). While "Make in India" is promoted vigorously, BOSS is not promoted. The above mentioned video promotion is still in Black Box. What is the problem in broadcasting the video if it is a part of "Make In India" ?

There are thousands of courses in hundreds of Indian Universities openly recommending Microsoft's proprietary products such as MS Windows, MS Word, MS Excel, MS Power Point etc in their Syllabi. I, being a teacher, really feel ashamed that the whole Education System (or the whole country ?) is run by Microsoft, when the free & open source alternatives are available and moreover they are made available by our own country for the sole purpose of replacing Microsoft products. Why they have not removed such commercial products from syllabi and replaced them with BOSS and other similar free and open source public domain software ?

On paper government has been successful in proving that it has declared a war against Microsoft and other commercial software giants in favor of our country but in reality they have put a red carpet for them allowing a strong iron grip on the nation. Getting a certificate from Microsoft with courses like MS-CIT and calling us as IT literate is a real tragic joke in India.
(Stephan Hawking has rightly said "The greatest enemy of knowledge is not ignorance, it is the illusion of knowledge.").


The situation is exactly the same as it was in 150 years ago before independence, the only difference being that Microsoft is now playing the role of East India Company.

We must not spend time in finding out who is/are responsible for this tragic state of the country. But pressurize government to implement BOSS immediately through an ordinance...

Note that no political party, no organization, no Indian can dare to oppose this ordinance once it is issued !

Please sign the petition and start QUIT INDIA - II movement for closed and proprietary software. Share the petition with as many Indians as possible. Also share it with FOSS communities around the world. I am sure FOSS supporters in other countries will also  come forward and sign the petition.

Thanks and Regards,

-- Milind

"Journey of thousand miles begins with one step" - Lao Tzu 

You can sign my petition by clicking here.

Thanks!
Milind Oka

title: Lagrange's Theorem Proof how to multiply sqrt(-1) values for subgroup H[1,i] (((GROUP THEORY))))
body:
PROGRAM FOR H=[1,-1]

clear;
clc;
G=[1,-1,sqrt(-1),-sqrt(-1)];
H=[1,-1]
i=1;
if H(i)*H(i+1)==H(i)|H(i)*H(i+1)==H(i+1) then
    if H(i)*H(i)==H(i)|H(i)*H(i)==H(i+1) then
        if H(i+1)*H(i+1)==H(i)|H(i+1)*H(i+1)==H(i+1) then
            printf("H is closed under multiplication\\n");
        else
            printf("H is not closed and hence H is not a group");
            abort;
        end
    end
end
if H(i)*H(i)==H(i) & H(i+1)*H(i)==H(i+1) then
    e=H(i);
    printf("e=%f is an unique identity element \\n",H(i));
else if H(i)*H(i+1)==H(i) & H(i+1)*H(i+1)==H(i+1) then
        e=H(i+1);
        printf("e=%f is an unique identity element \\n",H(i+1));
    else
        printf("No identity element exists \\n H is not a group \\n");
        abort;
    end
    end
    in1=e/H(i)
    in2=e/H(i+1)
    if in1==H(i)|in1==H(i+1) then
    printf("i=%f is an unique inverse element of %d \\n",in1,H(i));
    if in2==H(i)|in2==H(i+1) then
    printf("i=%f is an unique inverse element of %d \\n",in2,H(i+1));
    else
    printf("No inverse element exists \\n H is not a group \\n");
    abort
    end
end
printf("H satisfies all three axioms under multiplication \\n");
printf("Hence H is a group \\n");
printf("H is a subset of group G implies H is a subgroup of G\\n");
printf("Lagranges theorem : O(H) divides O(G)\\n");
n=length(G);
m=length(H);
printf("Order of G=%d\\n",n);
printf("Order of H=%d\\n",m);
k=n/m;
if modulo(n,m)==0 then
    printf("O(G)/O(H)=%d",k);
    printf("\\n Hence Lagranges theorem holds\\n");
    printf("Hence H is a subgroup of G\\n");
else
    printf("%d is not a divisor\\n",k);
    printf("\\n Hence Lagranges theorem does not holds\\n");
    printf("Hence H is not a subgroup of G\\n");
end 


This works 

but 

when H=[1,%i] ,[1,-%i] it does not work , it says this
"H is not closed and hence H is not a group"

and the entire program aborts .......can someone please help with this ??????

body:
I want to write a Ruby script to check if the layer found in DOM in Firebug for a page (For example: www.jira.com) is matching with the hash values declared in my script. Below is the Ruby script I have written:

I want to write a Ruby script to check if the layer found in DOM in Firebug for a page (For example: www.jira.com) is matching with the hash values declared in my script. Below is the Ruby script I have written:

require 'watir'

# Initialize the browser
browser = Watir::Browser.new(:chrome)

# Go to the page
browser.goto('www.jira.com')

# Initialize hash for what needs to be matched. I initiliazed this way because in future, if some more addition comes to the hash, it will be easy to fix
JIRA_DATA_LAYER = {
    'one' => {
              'event'     => 'gtm.js',
              'gtm.start' => 1468393184212,
             },
}

# Function to read the elements of datalayer of JIRA
def read_data_layer(browser)
    data_layer = browser.execute_script("return dataLayer")

    return data_layer
end

# Function to compare the values of JIRA got directly from the page
def compare_jira_data_layer(browser)
    result = []

    compare_data_layer = read_data_layer(browser)

    compare_data_layer[0].each do |key,value|
       result.push(key)
    end

    return result.join("\\n")
end

# Function to check if the hash created and values got from page matches
def jira_data_layer(browser, layer)
    message = []

    result_compare = compare_jira_data_layer(browser)

    message.push('Checking Jira Data Layer')

    JIRA_DATA_LAYER.each do |key, value|
        value.each do |data_layer_key, data_layer_value|
            if data_layer_value == result_compare
                result = 'matches - PASS'
            else
                result = 'does not match - FAIL'
            end

            message.push("#{data_layer_key} #{result}")
        end
    end

    return message.join("\\n")
end

# Read the elements of the dataLayer from the page
data_layer = read_data_layer(browser)

puts jira_data_layer(browser, data_layer)

title: Improvements requested for 'Create your own disk image'
body:
1. The Software Training >> Create your own disk image method gives FOSS category as primary filter. An alternative mechanism of language as primary filter is desirable. This shall be more useful as usually downloads of multiple topics of a particular language may be more desirable than the other way round.

2. There is no mechanism to remove an incorrectly made selection in the downloads chosen. This enhancement will be very helpful.

3. The limit of a single download of 1 GB is too less. If http downloads are a limitation then ftp access to content or methods to sync with additional content is desirable wherein repeated download of content can be avoided and consuming offline content becomes easier as it is produced.

title: hate talk in Competitive
body:
So I know there is the in-game report system, its just at the moment I don't trust and I find this too important to leave to a report system that I have so far not seen any results from personally. 

I was playing in competitive just a little bit ago with a friend. And we were using the team voice chat to talk, like normal. title: Omeka vs. Drupal: why might one use Omeka instead?
body:
Hi,

Posting the question here at your forum, and not the Drupal forum. The standaard reply on a Drupal forum would be: because we are more flexible, powerful, extensible... because we're sort of a framework and not a...

But I wonder what the Omeka community thinks about it all. Apologies in advance for a rather lengthy post.

A bit more specific pro's for both:
- Dublin core is in both
- OAI PMH is in both

Pro's for Omeka:
- Works out of the box
- Specifically tailored for collections

Pro's for Drupal:
- Huge community and plenty of developers anywhere in the world
- Any metadata can be added to Drupal
- A huge amount of modules
- lots of third party integrations
- Easily create multisites

title: tutorial 15 not working
body:
http://spoken-tutorial.org/watch/Scilab/Linear%2Bequations%2BGaussian%2BMethods/English/

In this tutorial the first loop in the code makes an UT array. Or, at least it's supposed to.

Looking at this code using the debugger with breaks set at 32 and 34 I get the following results for the loop indexes: k=1, j=2, i=2 for the first iteration of the code.

Line 32 shows the factor, line 34 shows the code to zero out the following columns below the index element.

At line 32: factor = A(2,1)/A(1,1) is evaluated at the given index values which is OK. A(1,1) to normalize the row and A(2,1) to get rid of the first col in the following row. That's OK.

At line 34 we get A(i,j)=A(i,j)-factor*A(k,j) which resolves to

A(2,2)=A(2,2)-factor*A(1,2) using the i, j, k values. Not good!

This code should resolve to

A(2,1)=A(2,1) - factor * A(1,1)

to set A(2,1) to zero, the rest of the loop changes the other elements in this row by the same factor. So this loop is screwed up. If I change the code so A(2,1) is used where it should, the element is now zero, but the code shows an index error when I run it. So I'll have to monkey around with the code to make the UT array, but there is definitely a problem with this example!

And the last loop back substitutes to get the solution: I hope the last loop works as I have not tried it yet!

I modified the original code to make debugging simpler: I hard wired in the A and b arrays, and deleted the back substitution section, so I can focus only on the UT matrix code.

title: naivegaussianelimination doesn't work - 2nd post, same problem
body: Having done some further investigation into this tutorials problem from the previous post (lecture 15) I further simplified the code to eliminate all the code in the first for loop except the line that creates the factor. I ran the code and expected to see all the modified b(i)'s as a result using the pause in the loop. But there was still a problem with the wrong number of parameters. Going back to some of my previous monkeying around with some of your examples, I recalled there being a function called factor(). Renaming factor to faktor the problem about the wrong number of parameters went away!  So this example has at least two problems!  This being the second one, and the  first is the wrong code inside the 3rd loop evaluating A(i,j).

title: Wrong statement
body:
I checked the script to see if I heard it wrong.  But both are wrong. 
You cannot say 'In the absence of lactose, it will block the RNA polymerase to transcribe the LacZ gene.'
I assume you mean LacI product is blocking RNA polymerase.  That means LacZ gene will not be transcribed.  
You make it sound like LacI product will block RNA polymerase and make it possible for LacZ gene transcription.

title: Wrong statement (again)
body:
Same mistake as before.  'Since the LacI is bound to the LacZ Operator region, it blocks the RNA polymerase to produce mRNA.'
Blocking RNA polymerase will not allow mRNA production.

title: Wrong terminology
body: Dissociation denotes reversible separation.  Enzyme cleavage of lactose is irreversible.  The earlier term 'cleaves' is correct, not 'dissociates'.  Many good texts are available.  Please study them.

title: wrong phrasing
body:
'Observe that LacY protein binds to the Cell Membrane.'
The protein doesn't bind to the cell membrane from inside or outside.  It is inserted into the membrane and allows the transport of lactose molecules into cells.

title: Ribosome
body:
'Ribosome is an RNA structure that reads mRNA strands to produce proteins.'
Ribosome is made up of RNA and proteins. 

These PhET interactive simulations are really good ways to learn concepts. If you must make tutorials on them, at least read up on your material first. Also, get someone to edit your scripts for language and content before you publish.

title: Title Statement (245)
body:
In the MARC field 245 (Title Statement) while typing the title of the book, the 1st letter of the title will be in capital letter and remaining all are in small letter except special name/any short form/country name etc.

Thank you
Dr. Anupam Chanda
Librarian
DECET, Guwahat, Assam

title: DDC No (082)
body:
In the MARC field (082) Item number has not been putted -(4.51 Mins)
In the MARC field (245) Title should be in running letter. Only the 1st letter will be in capital, except special case, short form, country etc. - (5.50 Mins)
In the MARC field (260) Symbols like : (Colon) after Publication place. ,(Coma) after Publishers and .(dot) after Date of publication are missing - (6.40 Mins)

Thank you
Dr. Anupam Chanda
Librarian
DECET, Guwahati, Assam

title: About Communication Gap..... between Public Librarians and Remote Centers
body:
Respected Sir/ Madam
There may be a communication gap of language between Public Librarians and Remote Centers, on the following points.
1. Some public librarians till not handled any software.
2. Training language in spoken tutorial in Hindi is preferable for public librarians but they wants instructions in local language from coordinator at the time of difficulty
3. Some college librarians are also registered for this programme, the level / speed of learning may be vary between public librarians and college librarians / staff.
4. In the registration process.... there is no options in the drop down list for public library .
5. Most of the public libraries are not yet registered due to information required (mandatory), regarding head of organization, Ph no. , email id. etc. So, may be registration process is critical to public librarians.
6. Till in my region no one can (public librarian) registered yet. Only College staff/ librarians are registered for this programme.

title: rules for variable names
body:
The tutorial states that variable names can start only with a letter or an underscore.
Any identifier in Java can start with a letter, a seperator(Underscore) or a currency symbol like $ or even \u20b9
letters can also be \u0a85 any letter from the Unicode character set.

title: Do we need to work only on this course material, or can we make use of any other topics along with the course material?
body:
Course outline for 3 Aug 2019 Linux Coordinators' workshop

1. Ubuntu Linux on VirtualBox
(a) Installing VirtualBox in Windows OS
(b) Installing VirtualBox on Ubuntu Linux OS
(c) Installing Ubuntu Linux OS in a VirtualBox

2. Linux
(a) Ubuntu Desktop 16.04
(b) Desktop Customization 16.04
(c) Installing software in Ubuntu Linux 16.04 OS
(d) Basic Commands
(e) General Purpose Utilities in Linux
(f) File System
(g) Working With Regular Files
(h) File Attributes
(i) Redirection Pipes
(j) Basics of System Administration

3. Bash
(a) Introduction to BASH shell scripting
(b) Basics of Shell Scripting
(c) Command line arguments and Quoting
(d) Globbing and Export command
(e) Array operations in BASH
(f) More on Arrays
(g) Conditional execution
(h) Nested and multilevel if elsif statements
(i) Logical Operators

4. Linux for Sys Ads
(a) Creating user account
(b) Assigning Groups on User Creation
(c) User Password management
(d) Modifying User Account
(e) Group Password and Login
(f) Administrating Group with gpasswd Command
(g) Modifying and Deleting Groups

I mean to define tolerances (e.g. Uniform, Normal etc...) to some parameters and then run a Monte Carlo analysis (e.g. 1000 runs) and check the effect of the variation to a given signal.

Do you have any simple example (e.g. simple RC filter) on how to make it? 

I do appreaciate your suggestions.

Thanks
Knot

#include<iostream>

int main()
{

    int i,j;

    cin>>i>>j;

   for(j=0;j<=2;j++)

        cin>>a[i][j];
    }

    }
    
    for(i=0;i<=2;i++){

}}}}

title: Setting up curved pipe case for velocity driven flow (Salome to OpenFOAM)
body:
Hello,

First of all, thank you to the Spoken tutorial team and Saurabh Sawant for this tutorial.
I successfully created the geometry in Salome and exported it to OpenFOAM.
I made the required changes from the Hagen Poiseuille tutorial and got the expected results.

I wanted to set up a simulation for the same geometry but this time I want the flow to driven by the velocity at the inlet. (Similar to the elbow tutorial of OpenFOAM but with one less input).

I set up the simulation with boundary conditions similar to the elbow tutorial. But after the simulation, I can only see the applied velocity at the inlet and nothing happens.

Could you please explain how I can set up a velocity driven flow?
I have all other files same as the file set up in the Hagen Poiseuille tutorial. 
Here are the changes I made to p & U files: (I have not included the redundant parts)

// * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * p * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * //
boundaryField
{
    inlet
    {
        type             zeroGradient;
    }

    outlet
    {
type            fixedValue;
        value           uniform 0;
    }

    walls
    {
        type             zeroGradient;
    }
}

// * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * *U* * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * * //
boundaryField
{
    inlet
    {
        type            fixedValue;
        value           uniform (1 0 0);
    }

    outlet
    {
        type            zeroGradient;
    }

    walls
    {
        type            noSlip;
    }
}

Thank you very much for your tutorials, they helped me a lot.

Use 45 hours and a rate of 10.50 per hour to test the program (the pay should be 498.75). You should use input to read a string and float() to convert the string to a number. Do not worry about error checking the user input unless you want to - you can assume the user types numbers properly. Do not name your variable sum or use the sum() function
